<article class="article">
  <h2>What is an EMI?</h2>
  <p>An EMI (Equated Monthly Instalment) is the fixed amount you pay your lender every month until a loan is fully repaid. Each EMI has two parts: interest on the outstanding balance, and repayment of principal. In the early years the interest component dominates; as the balance falls, more of each EMI goes toward principal. This calculator uses the standard reducing-balance method used by all Indian banks, NBFCs and housing finance companies.</p>

  <h2>EMI formula</h2>
  <div class="formula">EMI = P × r × (1 + r)<sup>n</sup> / ((1 + r)<sup>n</sup> − 1)</div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>P</strong> — loan amount (principal)</li>
    <li><strong>r</strong> — monthly interest rate = annual rate ÷ 12 ÷ 100</li>
    <li><strong>n</strong> — tenure in months</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Worked example</h2>
  <p>Suppose you take a home loan of ₹30,00,000 at 8.5% p.a. for 20 years. Here r = 8.5 ÷ 12 ÷ 100 = 0.007083 and n = 240 months. The formula gives an EMI of about <strong>₹26,035</strong>. Over 20 years you pay roughly ₹62.5 lakh in total, of which about ₹32.5 lakh is interest — more than the original loan itself. That is why even a small rate difference or a shorter tenure matters so much.</p>

  <h2>How to use this calculator</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Enter the loan amount, annual interest rate and tenure — results update instantly.</li>
    <li>The doughnut shows how your total repayment splits between principal and interest.</li>
    <li>Open the amortization schedule to see interest, principal and balance for every year.</li>
    <li>Use <em>Copy link</em> to share your exact calculation with anyone.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Tips to reduce your interest burden</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Prepay early.</strong> Prepayments in the first third of the tenure save the most interest, because that is when the interest component of each EMI is highest.</li>
    <li><strong>Choose tenure carefully.</strong> Stretching from 20 to 25 years cuts the EMI only modestly but adds several lakh in interest on a typical home loan.</li>
    <li><strong>Negotiate or refinance.</strong> Even a 0.25% lower rate on a ₹30 lakh, 20-year loan saves roughly ₹1.1 lakh over the tenure. If your bank will not match market rates, a balance transfer may be worth it.</li>
    <li><strong>One extra EMI a year</strong> paid as prepayment can shorten a 20-year loan by about 3 years.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<script>
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function () {
  function recalc() {
    var p = CM.val('p'), rate = CM.val('r'), yrs = CM.val('n');
    var r = rate / 1200, n = Math.round(yrs * 12);
    if (p <= 0 || n <= 0) return;
    var emi = r === 0 ? p / n : p * r * Math.pow(1 + r, n) / (Math.pow(1 + r, n) - 1);
    var total = emi * n, totInt = total - p;

    CM.set('out-emi', CM.inr(emi));
    CM.set('out-emi-sub', 'per month for ' + CM.num(yrs, 0) + ' years');
    CM.set('out-p', CM.inr(p));
    CM.set('out-int', CM.inr(totInt));
    CM.set('out-total', CM.inr(total));

    CM.doughnut('chart-split', ['Principal', 'Interest'], [p, totInt], ['--s1', '--s3']);

    var bal = p, labels = ['Y0'], balSeries = [p], rows = [];
    var yInt = 0, yPr = 0, year = 1;
    for (var mth = 1; mth <= n; mth++) {
      var i = bal * r, pr = emi - i;
      bal = Math.max(0, bal - pr);
      yInt += i; yPr += pr;
      if (mth % 12 === 0 || mth === n) {
        labels.push('Y' + year); balSeries.push(bal);
        rows.push([year, CM.inr(yPr), CM.inr(yInt), CM.inr(yPr + yInt), CM.inr(bal)]);
        yInt = 0; yPr = 0; year++;
      }
    }
    CM.lineChart('chart-bal', labels, [{ label: 'Outstanding balance', data: balSeries, role: '--s1', fill: true }]);
    CM.table('sched-out', ['Year', 'Principal paid', 'Interest paid', 'Total payment', 'Balance'], rows);
  }
  CM.bind(['p', 'r', 'n'], recalc);
});
</script>
